    <section id="gedittest"><title>GEdit Test Plan</title>
      <section id="tptoolandmenu"><title>Toolbar and menubar test</title>
        <para>&tgoal; Determine if orca reads the menubar and the sub menus.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Press F10 and right arrow across the menubar.  When reaching the help menu left arrow back to the file menu.  On the file menu down arrow to all the choices.</para>
        <para>&tresult; On the menubar orca should read each item followed by "menu".  When navigating the file menu orca should read each item followed by "..." if that item contains more options.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Determine if orca properly navigates the toolbar in flat review.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Use KP7 to move up to the toolbar.  Press KP6 to move to each toolbar item.  On each button press KP/ to activate the button.</para>
        <para>&tresult; Orca should read each button and when clicked with KP/ the appropriate action should be taken.</para>
      </section>
      <section id="tpdialogbox"><title>Dialog box test</title>
        <para>&tgoal; Determine if Orca correctly reads the "file open" dialog.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Open gedit and only using the arrows and enter navigate to the Change.log under your orca sub directory.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When traversing the directory structure orca should read each item telling the user if it is a file or folder.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Determine if Orca reads the find dialog.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Press CTRL+f to bring up the find dialog.  Type "Mike" and press enter.</para>
        <para>&tresult; When the find dialog comes up it should be read.  When enter is pressed on Mike orca should speak that the word has been found.</para>
        <para>&tgoal; Determine if Orca reads the "quit without saving dialog.</para>
        <para>&tprocedure; Delete the word Mike found in the last test and press CTRL+q.</para>
        <para>&tresult; Orca should speak the dialog warning the user that the changes will be lost.</para>

	  <para>&tgoal; Ability to  create and save a new document in Geditor </para>
	  <para>&tprocedure; Start up gedit by selecting  'Applications'->'Accessories'->'Text Editor'. Make some changes to the newly opened document.  Select the
	  option 'File'->'Save As' from the menubar. Enter a filename in the 'Save as..' dialog window.  Click on the 'OK' button.  Select the option 'File'->'Close'
	  from the menubar. Select the option 'File'->'Open' from the menubar. Specify the name of the document in the 'Open File..' dialog window.  Click on the
	  'OK' button.   Close gedit with either 'File'->'Quit' or by pressing Ctrl-Q>. </para>
	  <para>&tresult; A new text file is created.  The file is closed
	  from gedit.  The same text file is reopened is gedit.</para>

      </section>
